1. Check Cluster Health
Start by confirming the cluster itself is reachable and healthy.

kubectl cluster-info
kubectl get componentstatuses     # (deprecated but still useful on some clusters)
kubectl get nodes

What to look for:

API server reachable
All nodes in Ready state
No widespread failures


Node-Level Troubleshooting
If pods are not scheduling or are frequently restarting, check nodes.

kubectl describe node <node-name>


🔍 Common issues:

NotReady nodes
DiskPressure / MemoryPressure
Network issues
Kubelet not running

📌 If node is unhealthy:

Restart kubelet
Check node logs
Validate cloud provider / VM health


Pod Status Investigation

Most issues surface at the pod level.

kubectl get pods -n <namespace>
kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n <namespace>


🛑 Common pod states & causes

StatusLikely CausePendingNo nodes/resources, PVC issuesCrashLoopBackOffApp crash, bad configImagePullBackOffImage name/tag or registry authErrorApp start failure


4. Check Pod Logs
Always inspect logs next.

kubectl logs <pod-name> -n <namespace>
kubectl logs <pod-name> -c <container-name> -n <namespace>

 For restarting containers:
 kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous

Look for:

App crashes
Missing configs/secrets
Connection failures
Permission errors

6. Resource Constraints (CPU / Memory)

Pods may fail due to resource limits.

kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

🔍 Check:

OOMKilled → Memory limit too low
CPU throttling
Requests/limits mismatch

💡 Quick action:

Increase memory/CPU



7. Networking & Service Issues
If the app is running but unreachable:


kubectl get svc -n <namespace>
kubectl describe svc <service-name>
kubectl get endpoints <service-name>


8. Deployment & Rollout Problems
If an update failed:

kubectl get deploy -n <namespace>
kubectl rollout status deploy/<deployment-name>
kubectl rollout history deploy/<deployment-name>

Rollback if needed:

kubectl rollout undo deploy/<deployment-name>


9. Events: The Fastest Clue
Always check events—they often tell you exactly what’s wrong.

kubectl get events -n <namespace> --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp

📌 Events reveal:

Image pull failures
Scheduling errors
Volume mount issues



10. Quick “Golden Checklist”
When things break, ask these 5 questions:

Is the cluster & node healthy?
Is the pod running?
Are the logs clean?
Are configs/secrets correct?
Can the service reach the network?


